{
  "contentVersion": "1.0.0",
  "id": "G3",
  "type": "grammar",
  "title": "Core Particles I: は, が, の, か, を",
  "meta": {
    "level": "N5",
    "unlocksAfter": "N5.1",
    "focus": "Topic marking, subject marking, possession, questions, and object marking",
    "estimatedMinutes": 25,
    "particles": [
      "は",
      "が",
      "の",
      "か",
      "を"
    ],
    "grammarForms": [],
    "icon": "📌"
  },
  "sections": [
    {
      "type": "grammarIntro",
      "title": "The Particles that Build Every Sentence",
      "icon": "📌",
      "summary": "Particles are small words placed after nouns to show their grammatical role in a sentence.",
      "whyItMatters": "Get particles right and you'll be understood even with limited vocabulary. These five particles appear in almost every sentence you'll ever read or hear in Japanese.",
      "youWillLearn": [
        "は — marking the topic (what we're talking about)",
        "が — marking the subject (who does the action)",
        "の — connecting nouns and showing possession",
        "か — turning statements into questions, or meaning 'or'",
        "を — marking the direct object (what receives the action)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "grammarRule",
      "id": "rule_wa_topic",
      "pattern": [
        {
          "label": "TOPIC",
          "color": "topic",
          "text": "X"
        },
        {
          "label": "PARTICLE",
          "color": "particle",
          "text": "は"
        },
        {
          "label": "COMMENT",
          "color": "verb",
          "text": "..."
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "'As for X, ...' / 'Speaking of X, ...'",
      "explanation": "は tells the listener: 'I'm about to say something about X.' Everything after は is the comment about the topic. The topic is usually known information — something already established in the conversation.",
      "notes": [
        "は is written with the hiragana は (ha) but pronounced 'wa'.",
        "は can mark contrast: 母は先生だ、でも父は先生では ない (Mom is a teacher, but Dad is not a teacher).",
        "The topic doesn't have to be the grammatical subject of the verb."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "わたし",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "I"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "がくせい",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "student"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "I am a student.",
          "breakdown": "Topic: I → Comment: am a student"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "やさしい",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "kind"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "The teacher is kind.",
          "breakdown": "Topic: teacher → Comment: is kind"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "母",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "mother"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "にほんじん",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "Japanese"
            },
            {
              "text": "では",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "ありません",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "My mother is not Japanese.",
          "breakdown": "Topic: mother → Comment: is not Japanese"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "grammarRule",
      "id": "rule_ga_subject",
      "pattern": [
        {
          "label": "SUBJECT",
          "color": "subject",
          "text": "X"
        },
        {
          "label": "PARTICLE",
          "color": "particle",
          "text": "が"
        },
        {
          "label": "PREDICATE",
          "color": "verb",
          "text": "..."
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "X does/is [something]. (subject emphasis)",
      "explanation": "が marks the subject — the doer of the action or the entity being identified. Use が when you're introducing new information or when the sentence specifically identifies WHO or WHAT.",
      "notes": [
        "が is required after question words: だれが、何が (who, what — as subject).",
        "Certain predicates consistently take が as their subject marker: ある and いる (exist). Many 'feeling' and 'perception' predicates follow the same pattern.",
        "が marks the subject and introduces NEW information — emphasis is a side-effect of this new-information role, not its core function."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "だれ",
              "role": "subject",
              "gloss": "who"
            },
            {
              "text": "が",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            },
            {
              "text": "か",
              "role": "particle"
            }
          ],
          "en": "Who is the teacher?",
          "breakdown": "Subject (unknown): who → is a teacher?"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "母",
              "role": "subject",
              "gloss": "mother"
            },
            {
              "text": "が",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "My mother is the teacher. (identifying specifically her)",
          "breakdown": "Subject: mother → is the teacher (answering 'who?')"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "友だち",
              "role": "subject",
              "gloss": "friend"
            },
            {
              "text": "が",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "います",
              "role": "verb",
              "gloss": "exist (animate)"
            }
          ],
          "en": "There is a friend. / I have a friend.",
          "breakdown": "Subject: friend → exists"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "grammarComparison",
      "title": "は vs が — the Most Important Distinction",
      "items": [
        {
          "label": "は — Topic Marker",
          "color": "topic",
          "points": [
            "Marks what the sentence is about (the topic)",
            "Used for known or established information",
            "Can shift focus and mark contrast"
          ],
          "example": {
            "parts": [
              {
                "text": "母",
                "role": "topic"
              },
              {
                "text": "は",
                "role": "particle"
              },
              {
                "text": "先生",
                "role": "predicate"
              },
              {
                "text": "です",
                "role": "verb"
              }
            ],
            "en": "As for Mom, she is a teacher. (Mom is the topic)"
          }
        },
        {
          "label": "が — Subject Marker",
          "color": "subject",
          "points": [
            "Marks who performs the action (the subject)",
            "Used for new information or identification",
            "Required after だれ, 何, どれ as subject"
          ],
          "example": {
            "parts": [
              {
                "text": "母",
                "role": "subject"
              },
              {
                "text": "が",
                "role": "particle"
              },
              {
                "text": "先生",
                "role": "predicate"
              },
              {
                "text": "です",
                "role": "verb"
              }
            ],
            "en": "It's Mom who is the teacher. (Mom is specifically identified)"
          }
        }
      ],
      "tip": "Introducing new info or answering 'who/what'? → が. Commenting on something already known? → は."
    },
    {
      "type": "grammarRule",
      "id": "rule_no_possession",
      "pattern": [
        {
          "label": "OWNER",
          "color": "topic",
          "text": "A"
        },
        {
          "label": "PARTICLE",
          "color": "particle",
          "text": "の"
        },
        {
          "label": "OWNED",
          "color": "subject",
          "text": "B"
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "'A's B' — connecting two nouns",
      "explanation": "の links two nouns together. The first noun modifies or owns the second. Think of の as an apostrophe-s in English: わたしの本 = my book (literally 'I's book').",
      "notes": [
        "の can chain: 先生の友だちの母 = the teacher's friend's mother.",
        "の can stand in for a noun when it is clear from context: 先生のは どれですか？ (Which one is the teacher's?)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "わたし",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "I"
            },
            {
              "text": "の",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "友だち",
              "role": "subject",
              "gloss": "friend"
            }
          ],
          "en": "My friend (literally: I's friend)"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "の",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "なまえ",
              "role": "subject",
              "gloss": "name"
            }
          ],
          "en": "The teacher's name"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "母",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "mother"
            },
            {
              "text": "の",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "友だち",
              "role": "subject",
              "gloss": "friend"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "My mother's friend is a teacher."
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "わたし",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "I"
            },
            {
              "text": "の",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "パソコン",
              "role": "subject",
              "gloss": "computer"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "いい",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "good"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "My computer is good."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "grammarRule",
      "id": "rule_ka_question",
      "pattern": [
        {
          "label": "STATEMENT",
          "color": "predicate",
          "text": "..."
        },
        {
          "label": "PARTICLE",
          "color": "particle",
          "text": "か"
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "Is it ...? / Are you ...? (question marker)",
      "explanation": "Add か at the end of any statement to turn it into a yes/no question. No word order change needed — just add か. It can also mean 'or' between two items.",
      "notes": [
        "In casual speech, か is sometimes dropped and replaced by a rising intonation.",
        "か can also mean 'or': りんごかみかん (apple or mandarin)."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "がくせい",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "student"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            },
            {
              "text": "か",
              "role": "particle"
            }
          ],
          "en": "Are you a student?",
          "breakdown": "Statement: '(you) are a student' + か = question"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "やさしい",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "kind"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            },
            {
              "text": "か",
              "role": "particle"
            }
          ],
          "en": "Is the teacher kind?"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "grammarRule",
      "id": "rule_wo_object",
      "pattern": [
        {
          "label": "OBJECT",
          "color": "object",
          "text": "X"
        },
        {
          "label": "PARTICLE",
          "color": "particle",
          "text": "を"
        },
        {
          "label": "VERB",
          "color": "verb",
          "text": "..."
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "Do [verb] to/with X",
      "explanation": "を marks the direct object — the thing that the action is done to or with. It appears before transitive verbs (verbs that take an object, like 'eat', 'read', 'study', 'call').",
      "notes": [
        "を is written with the hiragana を (wo) but pronounced simply 'o'.",
        "を only appears with transitive verbs — verbs that can take a direct object.",
        "Special use: を can also mark movement through a space: こうえんをあるく (walk through the park)."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "わたし",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "I"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "object",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "を",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "よびます",
              "role": "verb",
              "gloss": "call"
            }
          ],
          "en": "I call the teacher.",
          "breakdown": "Object: teacher → Action: call"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "友だち",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "friend"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "にほんご",
              "role": "object",
              "gloss": "Japanese"
            },
            {
              "text": "を",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "べんきょうします",
              "role": "verb",
              "gloss": "study"
            }
          ],
          "en": "My friend studies Japanese.",
          "breakdown": "Object: Japanese → Action: study"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "わたし",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "I"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "なまえ",
              "role": "object",
              "gloss": "name"
            },
            {
              "text": "を",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "かきます",
              "role": "verb",
              "gloss": "write"
            }
          ],
          "en": "I write my name.",
          "breakdown": "Object: name → Action: write"
        }
      ]
    },
